  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's a real barrier many face daily. As a fitness trainer in Naples, I've seen how fear of being judged can hold people back, whether it's in the gym or a classroom. Stereotype threat happens when someone's identity—like gender or ethnicity—makes them anxious about performing poorly in a field they're trying to enter. For example, a girl might feel she's not smart enough in math because she's been told girls aren't good at it. This isn't about innate ability; it's about the mental load of worrying about others' expectations. I've noticed this in my own life too. When I started coaching kids, some of them would avoid challenges because they thought they'd be seen as 'less capable.' As a man who grew up in a family where education wasn't the focus, I know how important it is to create environments where people feel safe to try. We should address stereotype threat by changing how we talk about STEM. Instead of saying 'you're not cut out for this,' we should ask 'what do you enjoy?' and build confidence through small, achievable steps. In Naples, where community matters so much, we can use local groups to encourage kids to explore science through hands-on activities. The key is to make it personal, not theoretical. Let's stop labeling and start lifting each other up. After all, in the gym, we don't judge your form—we help you get stronger. STEM should work the same way.",
